**Nuclear War: Everyone is Preparing for the Worst**
The nine countries with nuclear weapons are currently increasing their preparations in case a conflict escalates to the point where the use of these weapons becomes necessary. This is revealed by the annual report of the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute (SIPRI), the most widely cited source of information on nuclear weapons. Massive modernization programs of nuclear arsenals are underway, and nuclear weapons are playing an increasingly important role in strategic thinking and the discourse of some leaders, such as Putin and Medvedev in Russia. According to SIPRI, nuclear weapons have not played a role as important in international relations since the Cold War. The United States has suspended its dialogue on nuclear stability with Russia, and last year, Moscow announced that it was leaving the New START treaty. The institute has stated that transparency on nuclear forces has decreased in both countries due to Russia's war against Ukraine. It is estimated that Russia has deployed about 36 additional nuclear warheads with its operational forces since January 2023. The United States, Russia, the United Kingdom, France, China, India, Pakistan, North Korea, and Israel are modernizing their nuclear arsenals, and several have deployed new nuclear systems in 2023. The nine countries have increased their spending on nuclear modernization by a third last year. The wars in Ukraine and Gaza explain the increase in tensions due to the deterioration of international security. Russia and the United States possess nearly 90% of all nuclear weapons. The global stockpile, estimated in January 2024 at 12,121 nuclear warheads, represents a reduction of 391 from the previous year. However, this is not reassuring. About 3,900 of these warheads have been deployed on missiles and aircraft, 60 more than in January 2023. The majority of these operational warheads belong to Russia and the United States. China has deployed some high-level operational warheads for the first time, according to SIPRI. 'While the total number of global nuclear warheads continues to decrease as Cold War-era weapons are gradually dismantled, we unfortunately continue to see an increase year after year in the number of operational nuclear warheads,' said Dan Smith, director of SIPRI. 'This trend is likely to accelerate in the years to come and is extremely worrying.'
