**Do we really need yet another type of nuclear weapon?**
The US Defense Authorization Act requires the development of a new nuclear-armed, sea-launched cruise missile (SLCM-N) capability, which will be placed on attack submarines and potentially warships. This decision has been a partisan issue, with previous presidents Obama and Trump having rejected or modified the program. The new weapon will add to the already $2 trillion nuclear modernization program, diverting funds and talent from conventional forces. The author argues that the need for SLCM-Ns is based on flawed nuclear deterrence theory and that it will not provide a credible deterrent. The author also raises concerns about the potential impact on US-Australia relations and the nuclear non-proliferation treaty. The article concludes that there is no good reason to develop SLCM-Ns and that it will only complicate the already complex nuclear modernization agenda.
